'''Kudo Shrine''' (くどじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Ōji|Q1346392|qid=Q1346392|1=Ōji, Nara}}, {{ill|lt=Kitakatsuragi District|Q1131013|qid=Q1131013|1=Kitakatsuragi District, Nara}}, {{ill|lt=Nara Prefecture|Q131287|qid=Q131287|1=Nara Prefecture}}.

It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}, and its former rank in the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system#shosha|Q712534|qid=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was village shrine. In the {{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|qid=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}<ref>{{Cite web |title=National Diet Library Digital Collection |url=https://dl.ndl.go.jp/pid/1273537/1/44 |website=dl.ndl.go.jp |access-date=2024-02-05}}</ref>, it is written as “Kudono Shrine” (クトノジンジャ).

=== Overview ===
The ''{{ill|lt=Shoku Nihongi|Q611399|qid=Q611399|1=Shoku Nihongi}}'' says that in {{ill|lt=Enryaku|Q1373176|qid=Q1373176|1=Enryaku}} 2 (783), it was ranked as a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=official shrine|1=UNKNOWN}} and granted the divine rank of Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade. It is also listed in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} as “Kudo no Kami, {{ill|lt=Heguri District|Q11483501|qid=Q11483501|1=Heguri district}}, {{ill|lt=Yamato Province|Q907495|qid=Q907495|1=Yamato Province}}.”

Also, at the second seat of {{ill|lt=Hirano Shrine|Q738971|qid=Q738971|1=Hirano Shrine}} (former {{ill|lt=kanpei taisha|Q712534|qid=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}) in Kita Ward, {{ill|lt=Kyoto|Q34600|qid=Q34600|1=Kyoto}}, founded at the time of the {{ill|lt=Heian-kyō relocation|Q1389395|qid=Q1389395|1=Juan Bautista Massa}} in Enryaku 13 (794), Kudo-no-Kami was enshrined after being transferred from this shrine<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=http://www.kamnavi.jp/as/ikoma/kudo.htm |title=[Kannabi] Kudo Shrine |access-date=2022-12-17}}</ref>.

The enshrined deities are Kudo Ōkami, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Hachiman Ōkami|1=Hachiman|qid=Q261637}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Sumiyoshi Ōkami|qid=Q1114013|1=Sumiyoshi sanjin}}, and {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Kasuga Ōkami|qid=Q11088805|1=Kasuga-no-Kami}}<ref>Shrine notice board</ref>.

In the {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} ''{{ill|lt=Jinja Meisaichō|Q11590704|qid=Q11590704|1=jinjameisaichou}}'', “Kudo-no-Kami” was not recorded, but in {{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|qid=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 43, Kudo-no-Kami was invited from Hirano Shrine (former kanpei taisha) and enshrined in the main sanctuary of Kudo Shrine, the original seat.

Kudo Ōkami is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=kitchen hearth deity|1=Kitchen God|qid=Q249178}}<ref>{{Cite web|title=Hirano Shrine|url=https://www.hiranojinja.com/home/gaiyo|access-date=2025-10-26}}</ref>.

Kudo Ōkami was conferred Senior First Rank in {{ill|lt=Eihō|Q1193881|qid=Q1193881|1=Eihō}} 1 ({{ill|lt=1081|Q19450|qid=Q19450|1=1081}})<ref>{{Cite web|title=Nara Prefecture Jinja-chō: Kudo Shrine|url=https://jinja-net.jp/jinjacho-nara/jsearch3nara.php?jinjya=5810|access-date=2025-10-29}}</ref>.

The oldest stone lantern at the shrine is from {{ill|lt=Ryakuō|Q1146182|qid=Q1146182|1=Ryakuō}} 1 (1338) in the {{ill|lt=Nanboku-chō period|Q264012|qid=Q264012|1=Nanboku-chō period}}, and a {{ill|lt=Kasuga Mandala|Q11513629|qid=Q11513629|1=Kasuga Mandalas}} with a box inscription from {{ill|lt=Bunmei (Japan)|Q1193544|qid=Q1193544|lt=Bunmei|1=Bunmei}} 8 (1476) is deposited at {{ill|lt=Nara National Museum|Q147312|qid=Q147312|1=Nara National Museum}}<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.town.oji.nara.jp/kakuka/chiikiseibi/chiikikoryu/ojicyorekishishiryoshitsu/ojibunkazai/148.html |title=Kudo Shrine / Ōji Town |access-date=2022-12-22 |publisher=Ōji Town}}</ref>.

=== Access ===
About 10 minutes on foot west of the north side of {{ill|lt=Ōji Station|Q856582|qid=Q856582|1=Ōji Station (Nara)}} ({{ill|lt=JR West|Q502125|qid=Q502125|1=West Japan Railway Company}} and {{ill|lt=Kintetsu|Q1531085|qid=Q1531085|1=Kintetsu Railway}}).

